06690nam a22006975i 9780822377849DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19981998ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223778497 a10.1515/97808223778492doi  a(DE-B1597)553033  a(OCoLC)913465432  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aJC263 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320/.09200aLaw as Politics :bCarl Schmitt's Critique of Liberalism /cDavid Dyzenhaus. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1998] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Why Carl Schmitt? -- tPART I. POLITICAL THEORY AND LAW -- tCarl Schmitt's Critique of Liberalism: Systematic Reconstruction and Countercriticism -- tThe Concept of the Political: A Key to Understanding Carl Schmitt's Constitutional Theory -- tFrom Legitimacy to Dictatorship-and Back Again: Leo Strauss's Critique of the Anti-Liberalism of Carl Schmitt -- tHostis Not Inimicus: Toward a Theory of the Public in the Work of Carl Schmitt -- tPluralism and the Crisis of Parliamentary Democracy -- tLiberalism as a "Metaphysical System": The Methodological Structure of Carl Schmitt's Critique of Political Rationalism -- tCarl Schmitt and the Paradox of Liberal Democracy -- tPART II. LECAL THEORY AND POLITICS -- tCarl Schmitt on Sovereignty and Constituent Power -- tThe 1933 "Break" in Carl Schmitt's Theory -- tThe Dilemmas of Dictatorship: Carl Schmi~t and Constitutional Emergency Powers -- tRevolutions and Constitutions: Hannah Arendt's Challenge to Carl Schmitt -- tCarl Schmitt's Internal Critique of Liberal Constitutionalism: Verfassungslehre as a Response to the Weimar State Crisis -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile antiliberal legal theorist Carl Schmitt has long been considered by Europeans to be one of this century's most significant political philosophers, recent challenges to the fundamental values of liberal democracies have made Schmitt's writings an unavoidable subject of debate in North America as well. In an effort to advance our understanding not only of Schmitt but of current problems of liberal democracy, David Dyzenhaus presents translations of classic German essays on Schmitt alongside more recent writings by distinguished political theorists and jurists. Neither a defense of nor an attack on Schmitt, Law as Politics offers the first balanced response to his powerful critique of liberalism.One of the major players in the 1920s debates, an outspoken critic of the Versailles Treaty and the Weimar Constitution, and a member of the Nazi party who provided juridical respectability to Hitler's policies, Schmitt contended that people are a polity only to the extent that they share common enemies. He saw the liberal notion of a peaceful world of universal citizens as a sheer impossibility and attributed the problems of Weimar to liberalism and its inability to cope with pluralism and political conflict. In the decade since his death, Schmitt's writings have been taken up by both the right and the left and scholars differ greatly in their evaluation of Schmitt's ideas. Law as Politics thematically organizes in one volume the varying engagements and confrontations with Schmitt's work and allows scholars to acknowledge-and therefore be in a better position to negotiate-an important paradox inscribed in the very nature of liberal democracy.Law as Politics will interest political philosophers, legal theorists, historians, and anyone interested in Schmitt's relevance to current discussions of liberalism.Contributors. Heiner Bielefeldt, Ronald Beiner, Ernst-Wolfgang Bockenforde, Renato Cristi, David Dyzenhaus, Robert Howse, Ellen Kennedy, Dominique Leydet, Ingeborg Maus, John P. McCormick, Reinhard Mehring, Chantal Mouffe